			<div class="lined-section">
				<h3>
					<img src="/images/ns-documentation/insignia.png" alt="Sprout insignia for Nightsprout." />
					<span>Chapter X: Our CSS Files</span>
					<div>“The Cascade Handles the Work so You Don't Have To!”</div>
				</h3>
				<div class="section">
					<p>Let's talk about <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Css">CSS</a> (By the way, if you are an extra-savvy web person, you might be interested to know that our CSS is derived from <a href="http://sass-lang.com/">SASS/SCSS</a>. We will also cover that topic <a href="#">later in this section</a>.). If you are unfamiliar with CSS, you can find a starter tutorial at <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/">w3schools</a>. If you're planning to make use of CSS to modify your theme, it is best you have some prior understanding of how it works. This section will <strong>not</strong> teach you how to write CSS. It is designed to teach those of you who know CSS how our CSS is set up so that you can tweak it to your own preferences. It is likely you will be completely satisfied with our many baked-in theme variations (great for beginning users) but we also want to make sure to give you as much control over your theme as possible. Heard enough? Let's get started.</p>
					<p>Your theme's visual presentation is controlled by two stylesheets:</p>
					<ol>
						<li><a href="#">screen.css</a></li>
						<li><a href="#">empire.css</a></li>
					</ol>
					<p>Screen.css is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Style_Sheets#CSS_frameworks">CSS Framework</a> that sets the presentation of the site to reasonable defaults. Nightsprout uses screen.css as a default for all of our Wordpress themes. Some of the automagical things it does include:</p>
					<ul>
						<li>Position everything on page,</li>
						<li>make the typography beautiful and consistent,</li>
						<li>tame form elements: inputs/buttons/etc.,</li>
						<li>create commonly-used elements, such as lined lists,</li>
						<li>... and more!</li>
					</ul>
					<p>One thing to note about screen.css is that it sets almost every HTML element to have the following rules applied:</p>
					<code class="prettyprint">
						<ol>
							<li>div, table, blockquote, code, pre, nav, address, cite,</li>
							<li>h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, p, ol, ul, li, dl, dt, dd,</li>
							<li>fieldset, legend, form, label, select,</li>
							<li>input[type="text"], input[type="email"], input[type="password"], textarea {</li>	
							<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;display: block;</li>
							<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;float: left;</li>
							<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;width: 100%;</li>
							<li>}</li>
						</ol>
					</code>
					<p>All Nightsprout themes use this block/float method of positioning because it is well-supported by all browsers. If you've used the <a href="http://blueprintcss.org/">Blueprint CSS</a> framework before, then you are probably already familiar with it. When making any custom changes to the CSS, be aware that elements should be floated or <a href="http://perishablepress.com/press/2009/12/06/new-clearfix-hack/">cleared</a>. In general, you do not need to edit screen.css file. Any changes you make to this file will have wide-reaching effects because it controls the most generalized style rules. Therefore, be weary if you choose to edit this file; a good rule of thumb would be <em>"Avoid making changes to screen.css!"</em>.</p>
					<p>The second file, empire.css, is where you will make changes should you choose to make any. Empire.css overrides screen.css and contains the unique look and feel to your theme. Some of the things it controls are:</p>
					<ul>
						<li>Sizing of various elements,</li>
						<li>colors and color themes,</li>
						<li>inclusion of images and other assets,</li>
						<li>presentation of the theme's unique elements,</li>
						<li>... and more!</li>
					</ul>
					<p>It is acceptable to edit empire.css. However, in the interest of easily maintaining any custom CSS you might add, we suggest overriding it instead. Simply add a third stylesheet which will contain your overrides and request that file after screen.css and empire.css.</p>
					<p>The next section will cover SCSS. You can read more about it on <a href="http://sass-lang.com/">their website</a>. If you know CSS, you'll love using SCSS. It takes away a lot of the headache of developing with plain CSS, especially when you use it with <a href="http://compass-style.org/">Compass</a>. In fact, that's why we use it!</p>
				</div>
				<!-- .section -->
				<h4>Our Suite of SCSS Files</h4>
				<p>This section is for people who know SASS/SCSS and want to get a little more in-depth with their customizations. Feel free to ignore it if this does not apply to you. As an added bonus for purchasing this theme, we've provided you with our source SCSS files free of charge. These SCSS files compile into the CSS we talked about in the previous section.</p>
				<p>As mentioned earlier, screen.css is the basic framework any Nightsprout theme starts with. However, this file is actually comprised of three SCSS files:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>screen.scss</li>
					<li>_vollkorn.scss</li>
					<li>_open-sans.scss</li>
				</ol>
				<p>Why do we include those two SCSS partials in screen.scss? Well, they are the magic sauce that makes everything line up nicely in your browser. Every font falls on a different vertical height. Therefore, each font needs its own special style rules to make it sit on the right line height. These font partials compensate for those differences. Nightsprout has created partials for several fonts found on <a href="http://www.google.com/webfonts">Google's open font API</a>. Screen.scss requests two font files - one for headers and one for body copy:</p>
				<code class="prettyprint">
					<ol>
						<li>@import "open-sans"; /* Request Nightsprout's partial for the Google font "Open Sans". */</li>
						<li>@import "vollkorn"; /* Request Nightsprout's partial for the Google font "Vollkorn". */</li>
						<li>&nbsp;</li>
						<li>html {</li>
						<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;@include font-theme-header-vollkorn; /* Include mixin from partial for headers. */</li>
						<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;@include font-theme-body-open-sans; /* Include mixin from partial for body copy and everything else. */</li>
						<li>}</li>
					</ol>
				</code>
				<p>If you wish to upgrade fonts on your page, we suggest using the design patterns found in the font partials we provide. It is possible to simply do a search/replace in the SCSS/CSS for a font name, but creating a new font partial is more robust and you'll find that you can make all the text line up to a very consistent baseline.</p>
				<p>Empire.css is also derived from a SCSS file (aptly named empire.scss). It is not comprised of other files but takes advantage of SCSS in two ways:</p>
				<ul>
					<li>All the colors have been broken out into a "Color Theme" section. This allows you to change the colors of the theme without having to do complex search/replaces on hex color values.</li>
					<li>Where possible, we have used mixins for browser-specific effects, such as box shadows, border radii, and gradients.</li>
				</ul>
				<p>The color feature is the most relevant to you. Rather than searching the document to change colors, you can simply edit the Color Theme section and make color changes there. The color variables are set up in such a way that they are grouped semantically, making it easier to make changes. Please note that your theme <strong>does</strong> ship with out-of-the-box color variations. This feature is simply there as an added bonus.</p>
